<DOC><DOCNO> AP890429-0080 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-29-89 1428EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     04-29 0244</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Haiti,0251</SECOND><HEAD>Rebel Soldiers Transferred To Provinces</HEAD><BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><TEXT>   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Military ruler Lt. Gen. ProsperAvril broke up a mutinous military unit by transferring most of thesoldiers to provincial garrisons, independent Radio Metropolereported Saturday.   The powerful Dessalines Barracks Battalion rebelled April 2after Avril discharged four of its officers who were implicated indrug trafficking.   Loyal troops put down the uprising, and unofficial reports sayat least 30 soldiers and civilians were killed and 75 wounded inthe fighting.   About 590 of the Dessalines Barracks' 613 enlisted men who havereported for duty in recent weeks boarded buses in front of armyheadquarters and were driven to new military posts scattered acrossthe impoverished Caribbean nation, Radio Metropole said.   The army high command has accepted the resignations of anunspecified number of Dessalines soldiers, Radio Metropole said,quoting army sources.   Avril has forced out around 140 officers in his realignment ofthe undisciplined 7,000-man army since he took power afternoncommissioned officers in the Presidential Guard overthrew Lt.Gen. Henri Namphy on Sept. 17, 1988.   Many of the discharged officers were suspected of being involvedin the shipment of cocaine from Colombia to the United States.   Washington has made a crackdown on drug trafficking a conditionfor restoring $70 million in Haitian aid. The aid was cut off afterelections planned for November 1987 were halted by gunmen alignedwith the ousted Duvalier dictatorship.</TEXT></DOC>